<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-473-147  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 473 147.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Engineering  Sept 1990 v22 n9 p16(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Who cares about data collection? (Automatic Identification)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fales, James F.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Good data collection techniques involve automatic identification,a systematic data collection method by means other than keyboardinput or manual notation.andP;  Automatic identification cuts errors inreporting data, and the data can be collected at a quicker ratethan with human involvement.andP;  Bar codes are error resistant at thecharacter level as well as at the word level.andP;  The bar codes canbe made even more foolproof with the addition of a data identifierand a preconceived data structure, such as they use in theautomotive industry.andP;  One study reveals that users are reportingpayback periods of five to 12 months on expenditures of $50,000 to$250,000 for a bar code data collection system.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     AutomationData CollectionBar CodesProductivityCostBusiness Planning.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>